<font color="#FF0000">THE INVASION</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan  4 10:05:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I served with the Vietnamese as an Advisor.  I lived, fought with them, played with their kids, ate dinner at their homes---poor as they were.  I spoke the languge and spent a good part of my spare time &quot;chatting&quot; with the private soldier.<br><br>
They did not view our presence as an &quot;invasion.&quot;  They were a bit puzzled at what they considered our altruism, but were most grateful that the people from the &quot;beautiful country&quot; were willing to fight and die to help them.<br><br>
   Even today, Americans are welcomed by the average Vietnamese.  Welcomed---not spat apon, as we were by your crowd doctor.<br>
 <br>
Their country was being invaded by another country, a country that they viewed as being oppersive and tryanical.<br>
Those who were Christian, had an instinctive loathing for the North and had fled from there by the hundreds of thouands. <br><br>
Many of the non-Christians looked apon the war as a struggle for indepedance.  They weren't fighting to protect what most Americans would consider a corrupt government, but as one soldier told me, fighting for the opportunity to freely chose what government they would have. <br><br>
 Corrupt as it was, most beleived that, given the oportunity, they could change it.  Under Communism, such would be impossible.<br><br>
And so they fought, and died.<br><br>
The US Gov. used to say that if Viet Nam fell, there woud be a blood-bath.  This was &quot;poo-poed&quot; by your crowd. <br><br>
 1.5 million died in Cambodia alone, tens of thousands died in Viet Nam, and thousands of others risked their lifes to try and escape in small boats.  Practicaly suicide.  Jus to get away from their &quot;liberators.&quot;<br><br>
Where where you and your protests then?<br><br>
While all of this was going on--NOT ONE OF YOU protested the what was happening.  Joan Baez, was the only one who tried to get her fellow protesters to protest the buchery.  No one joined her--she was a voice in the darkness.  Thought she was a trator at one time, but i respect the hell out her.  She--along with the people there---were abandoned by the &quot;Liberals.&quot;<br><br>
Where were you Doctor?  Did you protest the killing of hundreds of thousands of innocents?  The forced enslavement of the rest?  WHERE WERE YOU?  <br>
Of course not.  Neither you nor the rest of the &quot;holier then thou&quot; bunch of santicmonus moral cowards.<br><br>
Your &quot;high moral&quot; position and protests ended as soon as you were safe from the Draft and your precious bodys were safe from harm.<br><br>
Cowardness is easier to forgive then is hypocracy.<br><br>
I don't for one minute regret going to defend the freedom of a small, unimportant country.  I am proud that my country was willing to do so, and only regret our abandonment of our principles--and the people there who'd accepted our word.<br><br>
It was and remains, a &quot;Beau Geste.&quot; <br>
 
